extent.value: in 1 compact disk box and two card catalog drawers.

abstract.value: These seventeen interviews of longshoremen document their experiences working on waterfronts in New York, New Jersey, and London during the middle of the twentieth century. Subjects discussed include entry into the occupation, working conditions, characteristics of different cargoes, labor relations, relationship between rank and file union members and leadership, ethnic composition on the docks, and Communist Party activity on waterfront. The interviews were taken by Colin J. Davis and used in his 2003 book <title render="italic">Waterfront Revolts: New York and London Dockworkers, 1946-1961</title>.

p.value: Identification of item, date;  New York City Waterfront Oral History Collection; OH.060; Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives, New York University.
Donated by Colin J. Davis in 2007. The accession number associated with this gift is 1950.049.

Professor Colin J. Davis of the School of Social Science and Behavioral Sciences at the University of Alabama at Birmingham took these interviews as part of a study of the New York City waterfront. Interviews were used in Davis' 2003 book <title render="italic">Waterfront Revolts: New York and London Dockworkers, 1946-1961</title>.

The collection is contains seventeen interviews with longshoremen regarding their experiences working on the waterfront during the middle of the twentieth century. Subjects discussed include entry into the occupation, working conditions, characteristics of different cargoes, labor relations, relationship between rank and file union members and leadership, ethnic composition on docks, and Communist Party activity on waterfront. Interviewees worked in Manhattan, Brooklyn, and New Jersey. Additionally, there are four interviews with workers from the London, England docks: Pye, Donovan, Bloomberg, and Johns.
